<section xml:id="s_group_actions_stabilizers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Group actions: stabilizer</title>
    <definition xml:id="d_Gsets">
    <title>G-sets</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
        Let <m>G</m> be a group. A <term>G-set</term> is a nonempty set <m>A</m> together with a group action <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        Given <m>G</m>-sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, a <term><m>G</m>-set morphism</term> is a function <m>f\colon A\rightarrow B</m> satisfying 
        <men xml:id="eq_Gset_morphism">
            f(g\cdot a)=g\cdot f(a)
        </men>
    for all <m>g\in G</m> and <m>a\in A</m>. A <term><m>G</m>-set isomorphism</term> is a bijective <m>G</m>-set morphism.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    
    <definition xml:id="d_">
    <title>Stabilizers and kernels of actions</title>
    <notation>
        <usage><m>G_X</m></usage>
      <description>group action stabilizer of <m>X</m></description>
    </notation>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>G</m> be a group, and let <m>A</m> be a <m>G</m>-set.
        Given a <m>G</m>-set <m>A</m> and nonempty subset <m>X\subseteq A</m>, the <term>stabilizer</term> of <m>X</m> is the set <m>G_X</m> of all elements of <m>G</m> that fix every element of <m>X</m>: <ie/>, 
        <men xml:id="eq_stabilizer">
            G_X=\{g\in G\mid g\cdot x=x \text{ for all } x\in X\}
        </men>.
        In the case of a singleton <m>\{a\}</m>, we write <m>G_a</m> instead of <m>G_{\{a\}}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        The <term>kernel</term> of a a group action <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m> is 
        <me>
            G_A=\{g\in G\mid g\cdot a=a \text{ for all } a\in A\}
        </me>.
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <theorem xml:id="th_stab">
    <title>Stabilizers</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Let <m>G</m> be a group, and let <m>A</m> be a <m>G</m>-set. 
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Given any nonempty subset <m>X\subseteq A</m>, the stabilizer <m>G_X</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m>. 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                For all <m>a\in A</m> and <m>g\in G</m>, letting <m>a'=g\cdot a</m>, we have 
                <me>
                    G_{a'}=gG_ag^{-1}
                </me> 
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                The kernel of the action <m>G_A</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>G</m>. In fact, letting <m>\phi\colon G\rightarrow S_A</m> be the homomorphism associated to the group action <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m>, we have 
                <men xml:id="eq_kernel_cum_kernel">
                    G_A=\ker\phi
                </men>.

            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Left as an exercise. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Let <m>a'=g\cdot a</m>. We have 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>g'\in G_{a'} \amp \iff g'\cdot (g\cdot a)=g\cdot a </mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp \iff (g^{-1}g'g)\cdot a=a</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp \iff g^{-1}g'g\in G_a</mrow>
                        <mrow> \amp \iff g'\in gG_ag^{-1}</mrow>
                    </md>.
                    This proves <m>G_{a'}=gG_ag^{-1}</m>. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    The fact that <m>G_A=\ker\phi</m> follows essentially from the definition of <m>G_A</m> and <m>\phi</m>: <m>g\in G_A</m> if and only if <m>g\cdot a=a</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>, if and only if its associated  permutation <m>\phi_g\in S_A</m>, defined as <m>\phi_g(a)=g\cdot a</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>, is the identity map. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>
    
    <definition xml:id="d_faithful_transitive">
    <title>Permutation representation and faithfulness</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
        Given a group action <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m>, the corresponding homomorphism 
        <md>
            <mrow>\phi\colon G \amp \rightarrow S_A</mrow>
            <mrow>g \amp \mapsto \phi_g</mrow>
        </md>,
        where <m>\phi_g(a)=g\cdot a</m> for all <m>a\in A</m>, is called the <term>permutation representation</term> associated to the group action. The homomorphism 
        <me>
            \phi\colon G\rightarrow S_G
        </me>
        associated to the the action of <m>G</m> on itself by left multiplication is called the <term>regular permutation representation</term>. 
    </p>
    <p>
        A group action <m>G\times A\rightarrow A</m> is <term>faithful</term> if <m>G_A=\{e\}</m>: equivalently, if its associated permutation representation is injective. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    </definition>
    <corollary xml:id="cor_coset_space_action">
        <title>Action on coset space</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>H</m> be a subgroup of the group <m>G</m>, and consider the group action of <m>G</m> on <m>G/H</m> given by left multiplication
                <me>
                    g\cdot g'H=(gg')H
                </me>.
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            This action is transitive. 
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Let <m>A=G/H</m>. We have 
                            <men xml:id="eq_kernel_coset_action">
                                G_A=\bigcap_{g\in G}gHg^{-1}
                            </men>.
                            As a result, <m>G_A</m> is the largest normal subgroup contained in <m>H</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>

            </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Given any elements <m>gH, g'H\in G/H</m>, we have 
                            <me>
                                g'H=(g'g^{-1})\cdot gH
                            </me>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            We have 
                            <md>
                                <mrow>G_A \amp =\bigcap_{g\in G}G_{gH}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \bigcap_{g\in G}gG_Hg^{-1}</mrow>
                                <mrow> \amp = \bigcap_{g\in G}gHg^{-1}</mrow>
                            </md>,
                            where the last line follows from the fact that <m>g'\cdot H=H</m> if and only if <m>g'\in H</m>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Lastly, if <m>N</m> is a normal subgroup of <m>H</m>, then by definition we must have <m>N=gNg^{-1}\leq gHg^{-1}</m> for all <m>g\in G</m>. It follows that 
                            <me>
                                N\leq \bigcap_{g\in G}gHg^{-1}=G_A
                            </me>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </proof>
    </corollary>
    <theorem xml:id="th_cayley">
    <title>Cayley's theorem</title>
    <statement>
    <p>
    Every group <m>G</m> is isomorphic to a subgroup of <m>S_G</m>. If <m>\abs{G}=n&lt; \infty</m>, then <m>G</m> is isomorphic to a subgroup of <m>S_n</m>. 
    </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
    <p>
    Consider the action of <m>G</m> on itself by left multiplication, and corresponding regular permutation representation 
    <me>
        \phi\colon G\rightarrow S_G
    </me>.
    Since this action is faithful, <m>\ker\phi=\{e\}</m> and <m>\phi</m> is injective. We conclude that <m>\phi</m> is an isomorphism between <m>G</m> and the subgroup <m>\phi(G)\leq S_G</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    In the case where <m>\abs{G}=n&lt; \infty</m>, composing <m>\phi</m> with an isomorphism <m>\alpha\colon S_G\rightarrow S_n</m> yields an isomorphism between <m>G</m> and a subgroup of <m>S_n</m>. 
</p>
    </proof>
    </theorem>

    <theorem xml:id="th_index_p">
<title>Subgroups of prime index</title>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>G</m> be a finite group and let <m>p</m> be the smallest prime divisor of <m>\abs{G}</m>. If <m>H</m> is a subgroup of <m>G</m> of index <m>p</m>, then <m>H</m> is normal. 
</p>
</statement>
<proof>
<p>
    Consider the left multiplication action of <m>G</m> on the coset space <m>A=G/H</m> and the corresponding permutation representation 
    <me>
        \phi\colon G\rightarrow S_A
    </me>.
    By the first isomorphism theorem, we have 
    <me>
        G/\ker\phi\cong \phi(G)
    </me>,
    where <m>\phi(G)</m> is a subgroup of <m>S_A</m>. Note that since <m>A=G/H</m>, we have <m>\abs{A}=[G\colon H]=p</m>, and thus <m>\abs{S_A}=p!</m>.
</p>
<p>
    We claim <m>\ker\phi=H</m>, whence the result follows. From <xref ref="th_stab"/> we know that <m>\ker\phi\leq H</m>. It follows that 
    <me>
        \abs{\phi(G)}=[G\colon \ker\phi]=[G\colon H][H\colon \ker \phi=pq
    </me>.
    Next, since <m>pq=\abs{\phi(G)}\mid p!</m>, <m>q\mid (p-1)!</m>. Since furthermore <m>q\mid \abs{G}</m>, we see that <m>q</m> is a common divisor of <m>(p-1)!</m> and <m>\abs{G}</m>. But since all prime divisors of <m>(p-1)!</m> are less than <m>p</m>, we see that <m>(p-1)!</m> and <m>\abs{G}</m> are relatively prime! Thus <m>q=1</m> and <m>K=\im\phi</m>, as claimed. 
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>
</section>